08232nam a22009975i 9781400833580DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122010nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008335807 a10.1515/97814008335802doi  a(DE-B1597)467581  a(OCoLC)979579282  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aBUS0230002bisacsh04a338/.040922204aThe Invention of Enterprise :bEntrepreneurship from Ancient Mesopotamia to Modern Times /ced. by Joel Mokyr, William J. Baumol, David S. Landes.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2012] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (584 p.) :b6 halftones. 7 line illus. 21 tables. 3 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Kauffman Foundation Series on Innovation and Entrepreneurship00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface.The Entrepreneur in History -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Global Enterprise and Industrial Performance: An Overview -- tChapter 1. Entrepreneurs: From the Near Eastern Takeoff to the Roman Collapse -- tChapter 2. Neo-Babylonian Entrepreneurs -- tChapter 3. The Scale of Entrepreneurship in Middle Eastern History: Inhibitive Roles of Islamic Institutions -- tChapter 4. Entrepreneurs and Entrepreneurship in Medieval Europe -- tChapter 5. Tawney’s Century, 1540–1640: The Roots of Modern Capitalist Entrepreneurship -- tChapter 6. The Golden Age of the Dutch Republic -- tChapter 7. Entrepreneurship and the Industrial Revolution in Britain -- tChapter 8. Entrepreneurship in Britain, 1830–1900 -- tChapter 9. History of Entrepreneurship: Britain, 1900–2000 -- tChapter 10. History of Entrepreneurship -- tChapter 11. Entrepreneurship in France -- tChapter 12. Entrepreneurship in the Antebellum United States -- tChapter 13. Entrepreneurship in the United States, 1865–1920 -- tChapter 14. Entrepreneurship in the United States, 1920–2000 -- tChapter 15. An Examination of the Supply of Financial Credit to Entrepreneurs in Colonial India -- tChapter 16. Chinese Entrepreneurship since Its Late Imperial Period -- tChapter 17. Entrepreneurship in Pre–World War II Japan: The Role and Logic of the Zaibatsu -- tChapter 18. “Useful Knowledge” of Entrepreneurship: Some Implications of the History -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhether hailed as heroes or cast as threats to social order, entrepreneurs--and their innovations--have had an enormous influence on the growth and prosperity of nations. The Invention of Enterprise gathers together, for the first time, leading economic historians to explore the entrepreneur's role in society from antiquity to the present. Addressing social and institutional influences from a historical context, each chapter examines entrepreneurship during a particular period and in an important geographic location. The book chronicles the sweeping history of enterprise in Mesopotamia and Neo-Babylon; carries the reader through the Islamic Middle East; offers insights into the entrepreneurial history of China, Japan, and Colonial India; and describes the crucial role of the entrepreneur in innovative activity in Europe and the United States, from the medieval period to today. In considering the critical contributions of entrepreneurship, the authors discuss why entrepreneurial activities are not always productive and may even sabotage prosperity. They examine the institutions and restrictions that have enabled or impeded innovation, and the incentives for the adoption and dissemination of inventions. They also describe the wide variations in global entrepreneurial activity during different historical periods and the similarities in development, as well as entrepreneurship's role in economic growth. The book is filled with past examples and events that provide lessons for promoting and successfully pursuing contemporary entrepreneurship as a means of contributing to the welfare of society. The Invention of Enterprise lays out a definitive picture for all who seek an understanding of innovation's central place in our world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEntrepreneurshipxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aBaumol, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaumol, William J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCain, Louis P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Wellington K. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelderblom, Oscar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodley, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Margaret B. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHau, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuran, Timur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamoreaux, Naomi R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandes, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandes, David S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMokyr, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMokyr, Joel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMunro, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchramm, Carl J., econt